data.content:
MSTest has `CollectionAssert` and more specific asserts that give **better failure messages** than `Assert.IsTrue`:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Count checks
    Assert.AreNotEqual(0, users.Count);
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // All items match a condition
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");

    // Item exists
    Assert.IsNotNull(users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin"),
        "Expected exactly one Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

- **`Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count)`** — on failure says `Expected: 3, Actual: 5` vs. `IsTrue` just says `false`
- **`CollectionAssert`** — offers `Contains`, `AllItemsAreUnique`, `AllItemsAreNotNull`, `AreEquivalent` (same items, any order), `IsSubsetOf`, etc.
- **Add message strings** to any `Assert.IsTrue` you do keep — otherwise failures are impossible to diagnose
- **`SingleOrDefault` + `Assert.IsNotNull`** — avoids an exception from `Single` masking the test failure

**Other useful `CollectionAssert` methods:**

```csharp
// Same elements regardless of order
CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expectedList, actualList);

// Exact order matters
CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expectedList, actualList);

// Check membership
CollectionAssert.Contains(users, specificUser);
```

> **Tip:** If you find `CollectionAssert` too limited, the **FluentAssertions** NuGet package adds expressive syntax like `users.Should().OnlyContain(u => u.IsActive)`.
